			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2615">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I found &ldquo;Which Way to Siloam?&rdquo; insightful and riveting, with one disturbing exception: the author&rsquo;s intolerance and anger toward vegetarians. We are all trying to find our individual way through life. If choosing not to eat animals or animal products is right with someone&rsquo;s soul, so be it. I don&rsquo;t think vegetarians deserve to be ridiculed or have their lifestyle described as &ldquo;stupid.&rdquo; Acknowledging our differences with compassion and understanding also provides powerful healing.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Amy Stiles<br>Matteson, Illinois</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2616">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I have been a <strong>Sun</strong> subscriber for at least ten years, and have read many articles that seem devoid of truth, especially interviews with shamans, astrologers, and gurus. Most of these appeared harmless and were sometimes entertaining. But &ldquo;Which Way to Siloam?&rdquo; was a great disappointment. Do the editors really expect readers to believe that these quacks can push their hands through a person&rsquo;s flesh and remove tumors? Do the editors believe this themselves? People suffering from serious, debilitating illnesses can be susceptible to questionable treatments that do nothing but lighten their purses. Please do not be a party to this.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">John S. Doherty<br>Tampa, Florida</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2617">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I was mesmerized by Blaize Clement&rsquo;s account of her journey to see the healers. I&rsquo;m a nurse, and I tried to share her essay with a surgeon I work with, but he wouldn&rsquo;t read it. &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t believe in those psychic healers,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve seen David Copperfield do tricks, and to me it&rsquo;s the same thing.&rdquo; Still, I wonder, Is her essay true? And I wonder how many times she will have to visit the healers before her body is straight.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Susan Bauerle<br>Alta Loma, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2618">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I read Blaize Clement&rsquo;s piece on psychic surgeons. I didn&rsquo;t believe a word of it. The miracles she describes never happened anywhere near a reputable physician. Her healers have no last names, no hometowns, no identifying traits at all. I&rsquo;m surprised <strong>The Sun</strong> would print such crap.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Mark O’Brien<br>Berkeley, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence-respond fill-pattern-light" id="2619">
								<p><a href="/contributors/blaize-clement"><strong>Blaize Clement</strong></a> responds:</p>
							<p>There are people who love me and respect me and would trust me with their lives, but who don&rsquo;t believe a word of what I&rsquo;ve told them about the psychic surgeons. If it hadn&rsquo;t happened to me, I wouldn&rsquo;t believe it either, so I don&rsquo;t ever try to convince anybody or offer up any of the many theoretical explanations for the results. I&rsquo;m stuck with the fact that this is what happened, and I need to tell about it because that&rsquo;s my way of exploring its larger meaning for my life.</p>

<p>As to the fear that telling about my experience might cause some ignorant, gullible person to run off to a psychic surgeon instead of going to a medical doctor, the fact is that people who seek out nontraditional healers tend to be more aggressive, better educated, and more affluent than the average person. They take control of their own health, and while their minds are open, they&rsquo;re not so open-minded that their brains are liable to fall out. Instead of avoiding doctors, they&rsquo;re more likely to demand before-and-after X-rays so that they can evaluate the results of psychic surgery.</p>

<p>About my snide comment regarding vegetarians, I&rsquo;m a vegetarian myself, so I certainly don&rsquo;t think it&rsquo;s a stupid lifestyle. I do think it&rsquo;s stupid, however, to become so worried and obsessed about it that it destroys the joy in life.</p>
	</div>


					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
